pageSummaryWhy: Both my parent passed away last year of Cancer
story: This past year has been, as I’m sure it has for many people,  a challenge. I lost both my Mum and Dad to cancer last year and thought it was time to give something back to the people who cared for them throughout their last days. I love a drink and have probably taken it to the extreme over the past 8 months so time for a change for at least a month! I will be doing a dry January and will ride 113 miles over 31 days in January, this is the distance from my house in Hemel to Droitwich where my Mum and Dad lived. I will also shave my hair off on New Years Eve to start my journey. Thank you for your support 😊👍🏻 Oh and I will match pound for pound funds up to £200 🤷‍♂️

story:
Well, I know that I've made some rather vague posts this year about my health, but I'm going to break the vaguebooking and let you all know that I had a cancer scare a few months back- thankfully after a few rounds of tests it was found to be a false alarm but I know that many folks aren't so lucky and have to spend months and years of their lives undergoing painful treatment and mental hardship on the road to recovery.
I've decided to sign myself and also Tomas (whose life has also been drastically affected by cancer) for the MacMillan Mighty Miles hike through the Peak District on the 24th July, a fundraiser which will have us traipsing across one of the most beautiful parts of the country in an effort to raise money for this excellent charity.
I'd really appreciate any contributions - I've got a target of £250.00-even if it's just the price of a pint, it's appreciated :-)

story:
Those who know me will know that running is not my strong point. I'm much happier in a pool or with gloves and pads. However, with a challenging January ahead, and after a difficult few weeks, I have been inspired to take on a run challenge. So, in January, I will be aiming to complete 50km throughout the month.

I will be running in memory of mum, Deep Hunjan. When I first moved to Reading and DJ and I lived in the flat, mum would run down to me and we would run back up together. I would then complete my loop back to the flat. She was much better at running than me!

I am hoping to raise money for Macmillan, a charity which mum supported, With people close to me as well as those close to people I know, who have faced cancer in some way, it is a charity that has significance in my life.

Your support in donations, or simply keeping me motivated will be greatly appreciated.

pageSummary: I am doing 40 days of fitness for my 40th birthday because They need your money more than I do!
pageSummaryWhat: I am doing 40 days of fitness for my 40th birthday
pageSummaryWhy: They need your money more than I do!
story:
It has been such a rubbish year for everyone but it has made me realise that material things don't matter. Instead of receiving birthday presents I would prefer you to give a small donation to McMillan Cancer Support to help fund vital services for people who really need it.  My family and friends have been hit so hard in the last few years with cancer that I hope to give a little back to support people going through it now.

And I thought I would try get fit at the same time! Working from home has made me even lazier than before so I am going to commit myself to doing 40 days of fitness in the lead up to my birthday. I will start on Tuesday 12th January (because no one wants to start new things on Mondays!) And end on Saturday 20th February, the day before my 40th birthday!

pageSummary: Raising money for the British Heart Foundation
pageSummaryWhat: Raising money for the British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit this JustGiving page.

We are raising money in memory of Stephen Lowe who sadly passed away on 9 Dec 2020, aged 71. He died of a heart attack.

As well as a much loved husband, father and grandfather, Stephen was a talented and well known local artist, Rotarian and member of Walkern village community. He will be missed dreadfully by so many people but the seeds of his kindness, creativity, knowledge and love of life that he gave out to so many people will live on with them.  He was a man with a big, generous, but damaged heart.

The British Heart Foundation  funds  over £100 million of research into all heart and circulatory diseases and the causes of them. We would very much like to raise money to support this worthy cause. Any donation is greatly appreciated. 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

eventName: Andie climbing Everest and Kilimanjaro at home.
pageSummary: I am climbing my stairs every day to raise funds because we need to understand the importance of our hearts
pageSummaryWhat: I am climbing my stairs every day to raise funds
pageSummaryWhy: we need to understand the importance of our hearts
story:
HAPPY NEW YEAR 2021! 

This challenge is hardly unique and I won't be breaking any records (apart from the longest time to complete a fundraising event, perhaps!), but it is unique for me and will certainly be very challenging!

I don't have much energy. I am unfit and get out of breath climbing the stairs. Sometimes, on a very bad day, I have to climb up on all fours. I am blighted by depression and often fight with myself to get out of bed in the mornings. Then I fight to get motivated to do anything. Then I am exhausted from the effort of the fighting. My Blood Pressure is too high. I need to exercise to improve this, but I am usually too tired and/or lacking in motivation to do anything about it and often go for days on end without leaving the house. 

There is no way I can fundraise by running a Marathon!

So, I am setting myself a challenge with many benefits. 

1: It will improve my own health and fitness. 

2: It will raise money for various charities. I can't choose just one!

3: It will raise awareness of mental health issues; chronic fatigue/M.E./PVFS; heart conditions and strokes caused from high BP; FASD (Foetal Alcohol Syndrome).

So here is what I am going to do. I am no Captain Tom. I am no Skipping Sikh or even little Tony Hudgell. Things take a long time for me: what someone else can do in two days or two months will take me two years, so this challenge is long-term.

It is 755 days until my 60th birthday on 26th January 2023 (I told you this was a long-term project!). 

In that time, I am hoping to climb Mount Everest AND Kilimanjaro.

I have been to Everest Base Camp and trekked in the Himalayas. Some of my happiest memories ever are from those trips. I always planned to hike there again, but it is unlikely to happen, so I will climb Everest in my own home. 

Having lived in South Africa for 13 years, I have left a large part of my heart in the African continent, so it seems fitting to climb up to Kilimanjaro, "The Roof of Africa".

To climb Everest is more or less 58,070 steps.

To climb Kilimanjaro is roughly 38,670 steps.

Total: 96,740, which I'm rounding up to 100,000

There are 15 steps on our staircase. I will need to climb up them 8 or 9 times a day over 755 days to reach my goal. On some days I will manage more, on others less, or none at all, but this challenge is going to motivate me to get going. 

I have been practising since Christmas (because at the moment I can barely stumble upstairs!) and will start properly on 01.01.2021, finishing on 26.01.2023. 

I will have three birthdays in that time: my 58th, 59th and 60th (sad, but true!) So instead of sending me a card or a gift, please donate to the cause that takes your fancy the most.

A 2-year fundraising project is loooooooong, but slow and steady is how I win my races in life nowadays. I will post monthly updates and say thank you, thank you, thank you, in advance, for donating anything, however large or small, that you can.

With love,

Andie, 31.12.2020

story:
Due to personal health reasons, it has been a while since I have been able to set myself a physical challenge.  However a friend told me about the LEJOG virtual challenge which you can run or walk a total of 874 miles and you have  12 months in which to achieve it  I will only be counting the walks (and hopefully the odd run) tracked through Strava and won’t be including my general day to day steps. Charities have really lost out in 2020 on fundraising so I really wanted to do my small part for the BHF after everything they did for my dad and both my grandad’s too before. As I and my sister also have FH (google it 😂) it may in turn affect Erica and Flynn as it is genetic. So anything I raise helps the research for future generations. In addition my grandma has vascular dementia which is also researched by the BHF  ❤️❤️❤️❤️  


Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. story: Thank you so much for visiting my page. I am raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I would be so very grateful for your support. Having lost my beloved Grandad due to heart failure a few years ago now, I want to do everything I can for BHF to help prevent others from losing loved ones as I have. Reaching a target of £200 would be a huge achievement for me, and one I would be greatly proud of. Through extensive research, aided by charitable donations, BHF has helped to reduce the number of deaths from heart and cardiovascular related diseases by 50% in the UK. Sadly this is not enough, as the commonality of heart disease means that hundreds of lives are lost everyday, killing 1 in 4 in the UK. Thanks to the generous support from people like you, the BHF are able to research extensively into potential risk factors in the hope to create innovative new treatments. I hope you find it within your heart to donate! Thank you, Joe.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
pageSummary: We are running the Great North Run 2021 because we'd like to support such a great charity!
pageSummaryWhat: We are running the Great North Run 2021
pageSummaryWhy: we'd like to support such a great charity!
story:
Will and I have been volunteering for Guide Dogs for the past 2 years and have seen first hand the wonderful work that happens. We've had the privilege of boarding early training dogs from the Birmingham Mobility Team, and are now Stud Dog Holders for the National Breeding Centre looking after the lovely Kurtis!

We currently lots of dog walking, along with hockey (when allowed) and gym, but long distance running is definitely a real challenge for us. During COVID-19 our involvement with Guide Dogs has been a real motivator to keep going, keep positive, and look forward. So in that spirit, we've signed up for the Great Northern Run (half marathon), in the hope that we'll be able to raise some money so the Guide Dogs can keep bringing up the best little life changers! 

Guide Dogs say; In the UK today, almost two million people are living with sight loss and of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone. Many suffer from depression and struggle with feelings of isolation. Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss. We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. We work for a world where blind people no longer feel invisible, where the quality of their eye sight is genuinely the only difference between them and the rest of society. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling your needs and dreams. A world where being blind or partially sighted isn't what defines you.

story:
This January, myself and some of my family are kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. We will each be running (or poss swimming for Chloe if the pools are open!) 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). 

After all the festivities and over indulging, together with the cold and wet weather which January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep us going when we need it most. It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button! GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

There is also a slightly personal reason as to why I have decided to raise money for GOSH. My eldest daughter is currently in the process of being referred to GOSH so she can start seeing a specialist relating to her auto-immune condition and if GOSH are able to help her, I will be eternally grateful to them.

pageSummary: I'm walking more than distance of a marathon because we must continue to help this amazing charity.
pageSummaryWhat: I'm walking more than distance of a marathon
pageSummaryWhy: we must continue to help this amazing charity.
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

My dad and I will be walking from my house to Great Ormond Street Hospital (over the distance of a marathon) to raise money for their incredible work. The plan is for it to take 4 days! What this charity does is mind-boggling and we really need to show our support. This challenge will be tough but it is all for the staff and children of GOSH working hard around the clock to provide life-saving work to some phenomenally brave young people affected by serious illnesses.

Show your support for this amazing hospital and donate. Every little penny counts and would mean the world to me for lots of money to go to GOSH.

Thank you so much!

Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

I appreciate that this year has been pretty awful for everyone and that we have just come out the other side of Christmas and still in the throws of Covid.

I will do a mile a day even if I power walk!

Thank you in advance 💞🙏🏻💞

pageSummaryWhat: I am running 31 miles in January to raise money
pageSummaryWhy: they did everything they could to save our son
story:
This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking
part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to
raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). 

Our son Finn George Tomos Cross was born in the UK on 26th
September 2020 following
an uncomplicated pregnancy and subsequent birth. Despite the best medical
treatment, and not before making the greatest impact on the lives of all
who loved and cared for him, Finn passed away on 5th October 2020 from a rare
metabolic condition called OTC deficiency.

We lost our 9 day old baby boy & little brother Finn to a
rare metabolic condition called OTC deficiency. It meant his body was unable to
process protein, instead converting it to ammonia. It was a complete shock
following a positive pregnancy and birth. For 7 days, his life was in the hands
of a group of incredibly kind and talented people from various fields of
medicine, who did everything possible to save him. 



After a phenomenal and momentarily odds-defying fight, his body proved it was
unable to cope with the levels of protein necessary to live on, and we had to
let him go. Finn George Tomos Cross died in our arms on Monday 5th October at
10:31pm, surrounded by love. 



We want some good to come from this heartbreaking chapter of our lives.
Therefore, this January we will be kickstarting 2021 by taking part in
Running off Christmas. As a team we will be running 31 miles each
throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's
Charity (GOSH Charity) where Finn was treated. GOSH is a truly
inspirational place saving lives of so many little people on a daily basis.
They were a huge part of our lives, for a brief but unforgettable moment.

We love you Finn and always will 💙🌠 your Mummy, Daddy and big
brother Ezra xx #finngeorgetomoscross #finnslegacy



Please feel free to share & lets see what we can achieve together!

story:
This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). 

 I spent the first few months of my life in Great Ormond Street Hospital. They saved my life after I was born ten weeks prematurely and my lung was squashing my heart.  They cut most of my left lung away in order to save my life.  I still have the scars that have grown with me and I like to make elaborate stories about how i got them (being bitten by a shark is my favourite!)

  Apparently doctors said I would only reach 5ft and struggle with exercise in life.  I'm 5ft 4 and have done alright with the exercise albeit not done very much recently so am looking to kick start the year with this and what better motivation than GOSH!

After all the festivities and with the cold and wet weather January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep me going when I need it most.It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button!GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

Please donate if you can, if you can’t please show me some support. 

Great Ormond Street Hospital Childrens Charity (GOSH Charity) and McColls, the leading neighbourhood retailer, are delighted to announce a brand-new charity partnership that aims to raise £1million over the next three years.Seriously ill children from across the UK travel to Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH) for specialist treatment for rare and complex conditions.The money raised by McColls will help fund GOSH Charitys vital parent accommodation service, supporting the refurbishment of 'McColl's House', which brings families closer together when a child is receiving treatment.By partnering with GOSH Charity, McColls colleagues and customers will support families at the heart of their communities, right across the UK.

story: This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). In September 2020, my cousin Tommy and his wife Jen welcomed their second son Finn George Tomos Cross into the world, after a healthy, uncomplicated pregnancy and birth. Sadly after a few days at home introducing Finn to his big brother Ezra and other family, Finn became unwell and was subsequently rushed to Great Ormond Street Hospital where he was diagnosed with a rare metabolic disorder called OTC deficiency. For a week GOSH provided expert care and treatment to Finn, but tragically Finn passed away at 9 days old. I am running in Finn’s memory, and after all the festivities and with the cold and wet weather January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's important and life saving work will keep me going when I need it most. It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button! GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

pageSummary: I am doing the half marathon winterwalk in London because great ormond street saved my sons life.
pageSummaryWhat: I am doing the half marathon winterwalk in London
pageSummaryWhy: great ormond street saved my sons life.
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I am doing the winter walk (half marathon) in February 2021. 

Most of you may know, great ormond street saved my son (Alfie) when he was just 3 weeks old, Christmas Day 2013. GOSH hold a very special place in my heart; so doing this half marathon I can give back in any way I can. pageSummaryWhy: GOSH saved Ellie’s life from cancer aged 3!
story:
Welcome to the Bungle Bears fundraising page! 🧸

Firstly we would like to thank you for visiting our page. Secondly we would like to tell you the story behind our fundraising. 

When Ellie was 3 years old she was diagnosed with Wilms Tumour which is a rare kidney cancer and also known as nephroblastoma. Ellie was referred to GOSH and spent weeks fighting for her life. With the help of all the doctors & nurses and having her left kidney removed, Ellie is now 22 years cleared of cancer and lives a normal healthy lifestyle. 

Without the help of all the staff at GOSH, Ellie and her family could be on a completely different walk of life. So we will be completing the 25km Easter 50 Challenge and kindly asking if you could either donate, share with your friends or family and/or like a post to help spread awareness we would be much appreciated.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Over the course of the next month, between now and January 31st, I'll be attempting to cover a distance of one million metres (1,000km / 621 miles) between my Concept 2 rowing machine and Ski Erg. This equates to around 30km / 18.6 miles per day, split between the two machines. I'm estimating this will entail spending about two and a half hours on them every day for the next 34 days, with no rest days.

I'm doing this in loving memory of my father, Owen, who died in July 2020 from a very aggressive form of bile duct cancer. There was less than a month between him starting to feel unwell and passing away. I'd therefore like to raise as much money as possible for Cancer Research UK, whose vision is to bring forward the day when all cancers are cured.

The fundraising efforts of charities have been severely impacted by Covid-19, so every little bit helps. Please donate whatever you can.

Thank you.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Thanks for supporting PRIDE Trust's fundraising for Marie Curie.

Information and Resources:

Marie Curie provide care and support for people living with
terminal illness. They also assist the families of those who are unwell, and tend to their needs. Last year they cared for over 40,000 people across the UK.

  • £20 – could pay for one hour of vital nursing care for someone
    living with a terminal illness in the comfort of their own home.
  • £90 – could pay for half an evening’s care in a person’s home
    when they need it most.
  • £180 – could provide nine hours of nursing support in someone’s home through the night, bringing the expert care and comfort families need in very challenging situations.

story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

In loving memory of our Dad, Douglas McNaught. Grandad to Laura and Mark McNaught. Father-in-Law to Sally McNaught and Chris Randall. What a hole has been left in each of our families with the passing of Dad. Though wherever we look around our homes and gardens, so many fantastic DIY projects completed and in no small part thanks to Dad.

We miss Dad and are also thankful of his time and support. And not forgetting the skiing and cruise holidays - great memories, happy holidays.

Remembering also our Mum, Margaret McKerrow (nee Hill) McNaught. Mum and Dad now reunited and at peace. (Though we suspect Mum will be having words with him about how long it took him to finish his own conservatory!)

story:
In memory of Alan Armstrong

Alan was a loving, caring and selfless individual who loved his family and friends dearly. After a short battle with cancer, Alan sadly passed away on 26th December surrounded by family. To thank Marie Curie for all the amazing care and support they provided for Alan and his family, we would like to set up a fundraising page in order to say thank you for all their amazing work.  

Nurses worked effortlessly in order to get Alan home and out of hospital for Christmas. Alan was able to spend his last few days surrounded by loving friends and family. Without consistent support from both Marie curie and District nurses this wouldn't have been possible.

Thank you!

story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

pageSummary: 310000 because I want to raise money for  those who helped my mum
pageSummaryWhy: I want to raise money for  those who helped my mum
story: 22 years ago on the 14th October 1998 my mum lost her battle with Cancer! Her name was Rose, a single mother of 2 children who worked 2 jobs to support us all.. Mum was diagnosed on the January of the same year. She was only 44 years old 2 years younger than I am now!! I’m not going to go into any more detail because I have regrets and what ifs coming out of my ears.. I just want to raise money in her name to help others the way she was helped and cared for and I would appreciate any little donation you can manage.. we have all been touched by Cancer in some way and I hope and pray that some day there is a cure and no one has to dread this word on a visit to a doctor.. thank you in advance xx

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
In January 2020, we found out that my father had cancer. Over the following two months, we watched him deteriorate rapidly, in and out of hospital. Throughout this time, Marie Curie were unbelievable. The support and advice they gave us, alongside just general human kindness made everything that little bit easier. 

On 13th March 2020, dad passed away. Marie Curie enabled him to be at home with us right beside him the whole time. They helped us care for him for those final few weeks, and continued their support after as the pandemic lockdown began. Though he wouldn’t have told you, I know that one of his fears was being in a hospital at the end. Thankfully we managed to prevent that. 

Any support you can provide to help me give back to the charity that helped stop dad’s fear becoming a reality would be greatly appreciated. 

Thank you so much. 

————————————————

pageSummary: We're stepping forward on a sponsored walk because we love wildlife and want to make a difference.
pageSummaryWhat: We're stepping forward on a sponsored walk
pageSummaryWhy: we love wildlife and want to make a difference.
story:
IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY...

You might notice there's less wildlife than there used to be. That's because half of all UK species are in decline. We're losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate.

By donating, you are helping to build a greener future - the funds you raise will help WWF campaign to protect wildlife here and around the world.

Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now it's our time to give back. 

Any donation you can give will make a difference no matter how small.

With your help we'd love to reach our target of £100.

Thank you!

story:
On Sunday 24th January we are going for a walk to support the WWF's Big Winter Wander. The money raised will help protect wildlife here and around the world. We invite you to go for a walk too, wherever you are, and donate to this cause. Thanks!

Love Lee + Niki / Graves + Hop / Lykke Gropkins

Here's the official WWF text...

"IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice there's less wildlife than there used to be. That's because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back."

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
pageSummary: I am resuming jogging because I need to get fit and help others too.
pageSummaryWhy: I need to get fit and help others too.
story:
Climate change is affecting millions of the worlds poorest people, right now. More frequent and extreme weather is destroying homes, and wrecking lives. The people who have done the least to cause the climate emergency are being hit the hardest this is an injustice that can and must be stopped.

Oxfam is protecting families forced to flee their homes, supporting those hit by changing weather, making sure children have a chance of a future free from poverty and responding to the deadly threat of coronavirus. Through all of this, we rely on brilliant supporters like you to make sure our dedicated teams can be where they're needed most. We couldn't do our work without you.

Every donation, no matter how big or small, makes a difference. 

Together, we won't live with poverty.

charity.name: Unicef UK
story: Throughout the globe Covid-19 has spread rapidly. Although UK and Aus has seen its own share of illness and death we are very lucky enough to have first class healthcare service and government support in this crisis. Unfortunately others around the world are not so lucky. In an attempt to give back to those in need this February I have set myself the challenge to run 100km throughout the month in order to raise money for UNICEF. UNICEF, also known as the united nations children’s fund, is a United Nations agency responsible for providing humanitarian and developmental aid to children worldwide. We extend the invitation to anyone who would like to join us on our ‘Rona Run’ or set your own challenge for the month and help support those in need!

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk

pageSummary: I'm putting down the cokes, lattes, and pints because they need our help in Ethiopia
pageSummaryWhat: I'm putting down the cokes, lattes, and pints
pageSummaryWhy: they need our help in Ethiopia
story:
All donations will be doubled by the UK government until 4th of February 2021, so anything you can spare will make an impact! 

Shining the spotlight on our own flippancy when it comes to accessible clean water, I'm putting down the cokes, lattes, and pints this January by taking part in Water Aid's Just Water challenge. My teeth have never been happier...

Jokes aside, Water Aid is striving to bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world. With even the smallest donation, you can do your part in impacting peoples lives - and with UK-aid, all your donations are matched.

If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk
